comments: By selflessly giving of your time or gifts, you get something in return. Give for the sake of giving, not to get something in return.
I have no additional comments or suggestions.
I enjoyed participating in this study and I was happy to provide some insight. Thanks!
It was a wonderful study it feels good and enjoyable too.
early on in the study I accidentally tapped submit without making a selection. Wasn't intentional - sensitive trackpad.

There should definitely be a secondary set of options for the type of benefit. Much similarly to love languages, where it would be "Gifts" "Quality Time" or "Effort". I think some of the people had benefit in different ways, where one side benefit in a physical way, where the other benefit in an emotional way. 

Just feels like an important specification to me when I imagine any social interaction. 

For example : The religious meal from sue, if it was a Christian gathering, Sue would have benefit as Christians enjoy being able to do something good and selfless, whereas the other person gained from getting a meal from the other individual.
This was an interesting study, and I do wonder what the results of it will be.
